    "title": "Synchronous Apex",
    "permalink": "http://localhost:1313/sf-ohana/apex/synchronous/",
    "summary": "Synchronous Apex Synchronous Apex refers to code that executes immediately and waits for the operation to complete before moving to the next line of code.\nCommon Use Cases 1. Triggers Triggers execute synchronously when a DML operation occurs:\ntrigger AccountTrigger on Account (before insert, after update) { if (Trigger.isBefore \u0026amp;\u0026amp; Trigger.isInsert) { for (Account acc : Trigger.new) { // Validate account data if (String.isBlank(acc.Name)) { acc.addError(\u0026#39;Account Name is required\u0026#39;); } } } } 2.",
    "content": "Synchronous Apex Synchronous Apex refers to code that executes immediately and waits for the operation to complete before moving to the next line of code.\nCommon Use Cases 1. Triggers Triggers execute synchronously when a DML operation occurs:\ntrigger AccountTrigger on Account (before insert, after update) { if (Trigger.isBefore \u0026amp;\u0026amp; Trigger.isInsert) { for (Account acc : Trigger.new) { // Validate account data if (String.isBlank(acc.Name)) { acc.addError(\u0026#39;Account Name is required\u0026#39;); } } } } 2. Apex Classes Standard Apex class methods execute synchronously:\npublic class AccountService { public static void updateAccountRating(List\u0026lt;Account\u0026gt; accounts) { for (Account acc : accounts) { if (acc.AnnualRevenue \u0026gt; 1000000) { acc.Rating = \u0026#39;Hot\u0026#39;; } else if (acc.AnnualRevenue \u0026gt; 500000) { acc.Rating = \u0026#39;Warm\u0026#39;; } else { acc.Rating = \u0026#39;Cold\u0026#39;; } } update accounts; } } Governor Limits Synchronous Apex has specific governor limits:\nLimit Value SOQL queries 100 DML statements 150 CPU time 10,000 ms Heap size 6 MB Best Practices 1. Bulkify Your Code Always write code that handles multiple records:\n// Bad - Not bulkified for (Account acc : accounts) { Contact con = [SELECT Id FROM Contact WHERE AccountId = :acc.Id]; // Process contact } // Good - Bulkified Set\u0026lt;Id\u0026gt; accountIds = new Set\u0026lt;Id\u0026gt;(); for (Account acc : accounts) { accountIds.add(acc.Id); } Map\u0026lt;Id, Contact\u0026gt; contactMap = new Map\u0026lt;Id, Contact\u0026gt;( [SELECT Id, AccountId FROM Contact WHERE AccountId IN :accountIds] ); 2. Avoid SOQL in Loops // Bad for (Account acc : accounts) { List\u0026lt;Contact\u0026gt; contacts = [SELECT Id FROM Contact WHERE AccountId = :acc.Id]; } // Good Map\u0026lt;Id, List\u0026lt;Contact\u0026gt;\u0026gt; accountContactMap = new Map\u0026lt;Id, List\u0026lt;Contact\u0026gt;\u0026gt;(); for (Contact con : [SELECT Id, AccountId FROM Contact WHERE AccountId IN :accountIds]) { if (!accountContactMap.containsKey(con.AccountId)) { accountContactMap.put(con.AccountId, new List\u0026lt;Contact\u0026gt;()); } accountContactMap.get(con.AccountId).add(con); } 3. Use Collections Efficiently // Use Sets for unique values Set\u0026lt;Id\u0026gt; uniqueIds = new Set\u0026lt;Id\u0026gt;(); // Use Maps for quick lookups Map\u0026lt;Id, Account\u0026gt; accountMap = new Map\u0026lt;Id, Account\u0026gt;([SELECT Id, Name FROM Account]); // Use Lists for ordered collections List\u0026lt;Account\u0026gt; orderedAccounts = new List\u0026lt;Account\u0026gt;(); Common Patterns Trigger Framework public class TriggerHandler { public void run() { if (Trigger.isBefore) { if (Trigger.isInsert) { beforeInsert(); } else if (Trigger.isUpdate) { beforeUpdate(); } } // Additional logic } protected virtual void beforeInsert() {} protected virtual void beforeUpdate() {} } Error Handling public class AccountProcessor { public static void processAccounts(List\u0026lt;Account\u0026gt; accounts) { try { // Business logic update accounts; } catch (DmlException e) { // Log error System.debug(\u0026#39;Error: \u0026#39; + e.getMessage()); // Handle error appropriately throw new CustomException(\u0026#39;Failed to process accounts: \u0026#39; + e.getMessage()); } } } Performance Considerations Minimize Database Operations: Combine multiple DML operations when possible Use Selective SOQL: Always use WHERE clauses with indexed fields Lazy Loading: Only query data when needed Cache Results: Store frequently accessed data in static variables Testing Synchronous Apex @isTest private class AccountServiceTest { @isTest static void testUpdateAccountRating() { // Create test data List\u0026lt;Account\u0026gt; accounts = new List\u0026lt;Account\u0026gt;(); for (Integer i = 0; i \u0026lt; 200; i++) { accounts.add(new Account( Name = \u0026#39;Test Account \u0026#39; + i, AnnualRevenue = 1000000 * i )); } insert accounts; // Test the method Test.startTest(); AccountService.updateAccountRating(accounts); Test.stopTest(); // Verify results List\u0026lt;Account\u0026gt; updatedAccounts = [SELECT Id, Rating FROM Account]; System.assertEquals(200, updatedAccounts.size()); // Additional assertions } } ",
    "section": "apex",
    "date": "2026-03-13T02:17:40+05:30",
    "tags": ["apex","synchronous","triggers","classes"],
    "categories": null
